Tangling with the prison’s intrusive scrutiny and rigid rules turns these women into “quasi-inmates,” eroding the boundary between home and prison and altering their sense of intimacy, love, and justice. Yet Comfort also finds that with social welfare weakened, prisons are the most powerful public institutions available to women struggling to overcome untreated social ills and sustain relationships with marginalized men. As a result, they express great ambivalence about the prison and the control it exerts over their daily lives. An illuminating analysis of women caught in the shadow of America’s massive prison system, Comfort’s book will be essential for anyone concerned with the consequences of our punitive culture.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aConjugal visitszCaliforniazSan Quentin. 0aPrisonersxFamily relationshipszCaliforniazSan Quentin. 0aPrisoners' spouseszCaliforniazSan Quentin. 0aPrisonniersxConjointsxaliforniexSan Quentin. 0aPrisonniersxRelations familialesxCaliforniexSan Quentin. 0aVisites conjugalesxCaliforniexSan QuentinxCaliforniaxSan Quentin. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311063538640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226114682423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780226114682.jpg  a978-3-11-063538-6  University of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles